<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-859-710  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 859 710.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Sept 18 1989 v10 n37 p19(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Survey finds ad agencies behind in automation.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Altman, June.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Eighty four percent of the respondents in a survey of advertisingagencies plan to enlarge, modify or change their present computersystem within the next two years, signifying that their presentsystems are inadequate.andP;  Dennis Dolan, the author of the survey,believes that the agencies are dissatisfied because they have nottaken full advantage of automation capabilities in all facets ofthe business.andP;  He believes there has been automation only in theaccounting and financial sector because agencies tend not to makecapital investments that cannot be billed directly to clients.andO;Agencies without automated office systems will repeatedly lose outto those agencies that do have automated systems.andP;  The survey wassent to 1,400 agencies with billings over $5 million; of those,ten percent responded.andP;  More than 70 percent presently usecomputers, with 96 percent of the companies utilizingmicrocomputers exclusively.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Advertising AgenciesUser SurveyOffice Automation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Computer use by 140 advertising agencies. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>